Happy to announce the newest #R4DS online learning community project! #TidyTuesday is your weekly #tidyverse practice!

Each week we'll post data and a plot at https://t.co/8NaXR93uIX under the datasets link.

You clean the data and tweak the plot in R!
#rstats #ggplot2 https://t.co/sDaHsB8uwL

MOST IMPORTANT RULE!

0. Have fun! Connect with your fellow #RStats enthusiasts, and stay positive with your interactions! The goal of #TidyTuesday is to get better at R, no matter where you start!!
4. Use the hashtag #TidyTuesday on Twitter if you create your own version and would like to share it.

This week's #TidyTuesday function is from the stringr package! All of the column names have (%), and you can remove that with this code:

names(world_df) <- str_trim(
    str_remove_all(names(world_df), "[[:punct:]]")
    )

@drob Your #TidyTuesday videos inspired me to add this snippet into RStudio:  
snippet drob_plot
  count(${1}, sort = TRUE) %>%
  head(${2}) %>%
  mutate(${1} = reorder(${1}, n)) %>%
  ggplot(aes(${1}, n)) +
  geom_col() +
  coord_flip()

Might save you some valuable seconds!

Waarom vertel ik dit juist vandaag? 
Elke maandag is #TidyTuesday. Ik weet dat maandag zich niet echt lekker vertaalt naar Tuesday, maar op maandag rond 09.00 CT time, post @ThomasMock data (Hi Thomas!). 
Deze data wordt met goedkeuring gedeeld en is voor iedereen te gebruiken.

Er zijn wel een paar regels: 
1. Benoem altijd de source van de data, 
2. Als je iets post, gebruik de hashtag #TidyTuesday en deel hierbij altijd je code, 3. Je mag elkaars codes van feedback voorzien, maar blijf constructief en opbouwend.

Leuke vraag! Het commentaar is in het Engels zodat andere gebruikers ervan kunnen leren. Dat is het idee achter #TidyTuesday.
Variabelen is net wat je zelf kiest (ik gebruik meestal data1, data2...dataK).
Al mijn codes zijn trouwens te vinden op:
https://t.co/Ea4uMjxTZw https://t.co/5AWK5cRcw3

#TidyTuesday often contains numeric data with many decimals. Want to limit them? Gotta love substr(): it 
extracts or replaces a substring of a character string. 

Here, I deleted the last 4 decimals.

data4$grade <- substr(data4$grade, 1, nchar(data4$grade)-4)

My first contribution to #tidytuesday showing the usage of frames in Bob Ross's program. Firstly, we can see that he was not a big fan of framing his work (only 13% of them got a frame), of these 72% of the time he used the oval shape. https://t.co/namUzDIFf7

#tidytuesday Moreover, Bob Ross had a preference of which drawings he framed, being trees the favorite figure. While Aurora Boreal, cliff, dock, farm, fire, lakes, lighthouse, mill, moon, person, portrait and mill never got a frame in the programüôÅ. https://t.co/wizBtf3LyN

Lots of changes coming in the new #dplyr 1.0.0 release, including some #experimental ones! We wanted to highlight three of our favorites (1) Multiple value summaries (2) Type-based column selection, (3) Defining mutate() column position #rstats #tidyverse #TidyTuesday https://t.co/dYVSa2q71t

(1) The improved summarise() function allows multiple values to be computed / extracted by a single call summary, such as the range() function which returns the min and the max #rstats #tidyverse #tidytuesday https://t.co/2oPevcaLc2

(2) Eliminating the need for the select_if() function, select() now allows direct selection of columns based on their type, like here where we select all the character columns from the mpg data #rstats #tidyverse #tidytuesday https://t.co/PQ1I8NvB7u
(3) The position of new columns generated by mutate() can now be specified upon creation, with a simple .before and .after argument. #rstats #tidyverse #TidyTuesday https://t.co/2QoXvSxbPm

This presentation was really a love letter of appreciation for all the people contributing to and building on the #TidyTuesday project.

How big is the #TidyTuesday community?

Since 2018:
- 6,400 tweets and ~1,600 unique participants
- 2300 GitHub stars
- 118 weeks of data
